<procedure name="tuple_gen_sequence">
<interface>
<ic>
<par name="Start"/>
<par name="End"/>
<par name="Step"/>
</ic>
<oc>
<par name="Sequence"/>
</oc>
</interface>
<body>
<c>* </c>
<c>* This procedure generates a tuple with a sequence of equidistant values.</c>
<c>* [Start, Start + Step, Start + 2*Step, ... End]</c>
<c>* </c>
<c>* Input parameters:</c>
<c>* Start: Start value of the tuple</c>
<c>* End:   Maximum value for the last entry.</c>
<c>*        Note that the last entry of the resulting tuple may be less than End</c>
<c>* Step:  Increment value</c>
<c>* Assure that Step#0 and sgn(Start-End)#sgn(Step), else an error occurs</c>
<c>* </c>
<c>* Output parameter:</c>
<c>* Sequence: The resulting tuple [Start, Start + Step, Start + 2*Step, ... End]</c>
<c>* </c>
<l>Sequence := Start-Step+cumul(gen_tuple_const(int((End-Start)/Step)+1,Step))</l>
<l>return ()</l>
</body>
<docu id="tuple_gen_sequence">
<abstract lang="en_US">This procedure generates a tuple with a sequence of equidistant values.
[Start, Start + Step, Start + 2*Step, ... End].
Assure that Step#0 and sgn(Start-End)#sgn(Step), else an error occurs.</abstract>
<alternatives>
<item>tuple_gen_const</item>
</alternatives>
<attention lang="en_US">Assure that Step#0 and sgn(Start-End)#sgn(Step), else an error occurs.
</attention>
